41. Hoc tibi Paullus et Messalla]

‘’Paullus was a cognomen, which appears in several of the ‘ gentes;' but it is best known in connexion with the Aemilia gens, and the persons of L. Aemilius Paullus, who fell at Cannae (C. i. 12), his son the illustrious conqueror of Perseus, and the younger Scipio Africanus, son of the latter. The Messallae belonged to the Valeria gens, one of the oldest in Rome. This branch of the ‘gens' were highly distinguished, but Horace introduces the name probably out of compliment to his friend Corvinus, for whom he wrote C. iii. 21. As to ‘ hoc,' in the sense of ‘propter hoc,' see S. i. 46 n.
